3. A professor wants to know if her introductory statistics class has a good grasp of basic math. Six students are chosen at random from the class and given a math proficiency test. The professor wants the class to be able to score above 70 on the test. The six students get scores of 62, 92, 75, 68, 83, and 95. Can the professor have 90 percent confidence that the mean score for the class on the test would be above 70?¶

[T-Critical Value- 1.71, One Tail, Reject]¶

In [38]:
#data set
sample = [62, 92, 75, 68, 83, 95]
n = len(sample)
#H0
mu = 70
c = 90
alpha = 10
#one tailed t test
In [41]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_1samp
stats, pValue = ttest_1samp(sample,mu)
print(f'stats: {stats}, pValue: {pValue}')
if pValue > .10: print("Rejecting Null hypothesis")
else : print("Fail to reject Null hypothesis")

stats: 1.7053136360191492, pValue: 0.14885362711300268
Rejecting Null hypothesis

4. A Little League baseball coach wants to know if his team is representative of other teams in scoring runs. Nationally, the average number of runs scored by a Little League team in a game is 5.7. He chooses five games at random in which his team scored 5 , 9, 4, 11, and 8 runs. Is it likely that his team's scores could have come from the national distribution? Assume an alpha level of 0.05. [T-Critical Value- 1.32, Two Tail, Accept]¶

sample = [5 , 9, 4, 11, 8]
alpha = 0.05
In [47]:

print(f'stats: {stats}, pValue: {pValue}')
if pValue == alpha: print("Rejecting Null hypothesis")
else : print("Fail to reject Null hypothesis")

11. The amount of a certain trace element in blood is known to vary with a standard deviation of 14.1 ppm (parts per million) for male blood donors and 9.5 ppm for female donors. Random samples of 75 male and 50 female donors yield concentration means of 28 and 33 ppm, respectively. What is the likelihood that the population means of concentrations of the element are the same for men and women?¶

In [129]:
#data set
MaleSD = 14.1
FemaleSD = 9.5
MaleN = 75
FemaleN = 50
MaleMean = 28
FemaleMean = 33
In [132]:
import numpy as np
zTest = (MaleMean-FemaleMean)/np.sqrt((MaleSD**2/MaleN)+(FemaleSD**2/FemaleN))
print(f'zTest = {zTest}')

zTest = -2.368684181472862

12. The following data is given Calculate the Anova Coefficient.¶

Types of Animals Number of animals Average Domestic animals Standard Deviation
Dogs 5 12 2
Cats 5 16 1
Hamsters 5 20 4

In [144]:
#data set
import pandas as pd
df = pd.read_csv('p12 excel to csv.csv')
In [145]:
import scipy.stats as stats
stats,fvalue=stats.f_oneway(df['Type']=="Dogs",df['Type']=="Cats",df['Type']=="Hamsters")
print(f'stats: {stats}, fvalue: {fvalue}')
if fvalue < 0.05: print("Fail to reject Null hypothesis")
else : print("Rejecting Null hypothesis")

Rejecting Null hypothesis

14. Perform Chi-square test.¶

In [149]:

import numpy as np

a1 = [6, 4, 5, 10]
a2 = [8, 5, 3, 3]
a3 = [5, 4, 8, 4]
a4 = [4, 11, 7, 13]
a5 = [5, 8, 7, 6]
a6 = [7, 3, 5, 9]

dice1 = np.array([a1, a2, a3, a4, a5, a6])
In [150]:
from scipy import stats
chi2, p, ddof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency( dice1 )
msg = "Test Statistic: {}\np-value: {}\nDegrees of Freedom: {}\n"
print(msg.format( chi2, p, ddof ) )
print(expected)
